  <p>World War II inspired a great deal of mathematical work. The British developed a series of computational devices
    designed to do calculations required to break German codes. These devices culminated in <term>Colossus</term>, the
    world’s first electronic digital computer that was all programmable. Operators could reprogram the machine by
    changing switches and rewiring connections. Colossus could not compute any possible program, but it could be
    <q>reprogrammed</q> to solve different problems relating to the breaking of codes.</p>

  <video xml:id="yt_7cDeG3hyraA" youtube="7cDeG3hyraA" width="auto" />

  <p xml:id="the-first-generation-1">In 1946, the US finished work on <term>ENIAC</term>, designed to calculate
    artillery firing tables for the army. It is regarded as the first truly general-purpose computer - it could run an
    arbitrary series of mathematical operations. But, like the Colossus, its program was represented through the
    physical wiring of the machine. Unlike Colossus, which was part of an ultra-secret British program, the ENIAC was
    widely known of.</p>
